387. Am J Public Health. 2002 Mar;92(3):365-6. doi: 10.2105/ajph.92.3.365.

Effect of nevirapine toxicity on choice of perinatal HIV prevention strategies.

Stringer JS(1), Sinkala M, Rouse DJ, Goldenberg RL, Vermund SH.

Author information:
(1)Center for Research in Women's Health, University of Alabama at Birmingham, 
Birmingham, AL, USA. stringer@uab.edu

OBJECTIVES: This study evaluated the validity of concerns about the toxicity of 
nevirapine (NVP) that have delayed its implementation as a perinatal HIV 
prevention strategy.
METHODS: A decision analysis model compared 3 strategies: single-dose NVP, 
short-course zidovudine (ZDV), and no intervention.
RESULTS: NVP would prevent more deaths than ZDV and no intervention as long as 
the rate of NVP toxicity did not exceed, respectively, 9 times that observed in 
the earlier NVP clinical trial and 42 times that observed in the clinical trial. 
NVP would be economically preferable to ZDV as long as the rate of toxicity did 
not exceed 22 times that observed in the clinical trial.
CONCLUSIONS: Field implementation of NVP should not be delayed by concerns about 
its toxicity.

